NEURAL DX WATCHER V4.3 üõ∞Ô∏è Introduction

NEURAL DX WATCHER V4.3 is a next-generation web application designed specifically for amateur radio operators (DXers). It offers a real-time dashboard for tracking DX spots (distant stations) on HF and VHF/UHF bands, complemented by an advanced cognitive analysis module. The goal is to centralize propagation data, alerts, activity history, and mapping so you never miss a DX opportunity.

This version 4.3 incorporates very short-term prediction granularity (30 min / 1h) into its AI model and ensures robust, portable navigation between its modules.

‚ú® General Features

    Real-Time: Instant display of DX spots.

    Customizable Panels: Drag & Drop functionality to organize panels on both pages (Dashboard and Analysis). The order is saved locally.

    Themes: Simple toggle between SoftTech, Matrix, and Dark modes (synchronized across pages).

    Portability: Smooth navigation between the Dashboard and Analysis pages, regardless of the server environment.

1. DASHBOARD (index.html) - The Real-Time Control Center

The Dashboard is the application's main page, designed to provide an immediate and interactive view of global DX activity.
Module	Detailed Description
Real-Time DX Spots	Dynamic and filterable list of all received spots. Critical spots (DX Priority Score > 70) are highlighted to alert the operator.
Advanced Voice Synthesis	Audio announcement of new spots. A üîä VOICE ON/OFF button allows the voice to be toggled on or off.
Voice Distance Filter	A selector allows voice announcements to be filtered based on distance (relative to your QRA). Options include: ALL, < 5000 km, 5000 - 10000 km, and > 10000 km (for "Long Haul" DX).
Integrated Mapping	Two separate Leaflet maps: HF and VHF/UHF. They display the location of your QTH and active DX spots in real time.
Activity History	A band activity graph over a 12-hour window, with 30-minute granularity, essential for identifying regular opening windows.
Watchlist	Allows adding and removing priority callsigns. Spots matching your Watchlist are highlighted.
QRA Management	A form allows you to quickly set your QRA locator. The update is immediate, and the QRA is displayed at the top of the page.
Surge Alerts	Detection and display of unusual activity spikes (red alerts) on a given band, signaling a sudden opening.
2. AI INSIGHT (analysis.html) - 24H Analysis Module

Accessible via the üìä AI INSIGHT button, this page uses the AI model to digest DXCC data from the last 24 hours and provide projections and rarity statistics.
Module	Detailed Description
COGNITIVE DX FORECAST (NEXT 48H)	Global propagation prediction based on the NEURAL v4.3 model. This line graph is vital for activity planning.
New Short-Term Forecast Horizons	The X-axis (Time) now includes very short-term horizons for immediate decision-making: H+0.5 (30 min), H+1 (1 hour), H+6, H+24, and H+48.
Advanced DXCC Metrics	Displays three key metrics based on the last 24 hours of activity: Calls Spotted > 10,000 km, Rarity Rate (SPD > 70), and Absolute Rare Spots (SPD > 70) (list of rare DXCC spotted).
Unique DXCC by Mode	Bar chart showing the concentration of unique DXCC worked by mode (FT8, CW, SSB...). Useful for activity prioritization.
Unique DXCC by Band	Bar chart showing the concentration of unique DXCC worked by band (20m, 15m, 40m...). Useful for propagation optimization.
üì∏ Interface Overview
‚öôÔ∏è Installation & Startup

This project is built on Python (Flask) for the backend and HTML/CSS/JavaScript (Leaflet, Chart.js) for the client interface.
Prerequisites

    Python 3.x

    Internet Access

    Python libraries listed in requirements.txt (or install manually: flask, telnetlib, requests, feedparser, etc.)

Startup Steps

    Clone the repository:
    Bash

git clone gh repo clone Eric738/Spot-Watcher-DX
cd neural-dx-watcher-v4

Install Python dependencies:
Bash

pip install -r requirements.txt

Configure your QRA: Open webapp.py and modify the configuration variables at the beginning of the file, especially MY_CALL and DEFAULT_QRA.

Launch the application:
Bash

    python webapp.py

    The application will be accessible via your browser at the default address: http://127.0.0.1:8000 (or the configured port).

üõ†Ô∏è Configuration (webapp.py)

The main application parameters are located at the beginning of the webapp.py file:
Variable	Description	Default Value
MY_CALL	Your callsign.	F1SMV
DEFAULT_QRA	Your QRA locator (e.g., JN23).	JN23
SPD_THRESHOLD	DX Priority Score threshold for alerts (spots in red).	70
SPOT_LIFETIME	Duration a spot remains active (in seconds).	1800 (30 minutes)

